# We will extract stock data using a Python library. We will use the yfinance library,
# it allows us to extract data for stocks returning data in a pandas dataframe. 

# Install required packages
!pip install yfinance
!pip install pandas
!pip install matplotlib

# Import the necessary libraries
import yfinance as yf
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import json
import urllib.request
import os

# Setting up inline plotting for local Jupyter Notebook
%matplotlib inline

# Download the apple.json file
url = "https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-PY0220EN-SkillsNetwork/data/apple.json"
file_path = "apple.json"

# Download the file from `url` and save it locally under `file_path`:
urllib.request.urlretrieve(url, file_path)
print("File downloaded and saved at:", os.path.abspath(file_path))

# Using the Ticker module to create an object for Apple (AAPL)
apple = yf.Ticker('AAPL')

# Load stock info from the JSON file
with open(file_path) as json_file:
    apple_info = json.load(json_file)

# Display the stock info
print(apple_info)

# Display the country information from the stock info
print(apple_info['country'])

# Extracting share price data
apple_share_price_data = apple.history(period="max")
print(apple_share_price_data.head())

# Resetting the index to use Date as a column
apple_share_price_data.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Plotting the share price data
apple_share_price_data.plot(x="Date", y="Open", title="Apple Share Price Over Time")
plt.show()

# Extracting and plotting dividends
apple.dividends.plot(title="Apple Dividends Over Time")
plt.show()

# Summary
# Installation: Install required packages.
# Imports: Import necessary libraries.
# Plotting Setup: Set up inline plotting.
# Data Download: Download apple.json file.
# Data Loading: Create Ticker object and load JSON data.
# Data Display: Print stock and country info.
# Share Price Data: Fetch, reset index, and plot share price data.
# Dividends Data: Fetch and plot dividends data.

# 2nd project. Extracting Stock Data Using a Web Scraping
!pip install pandas
!pip install requests
!pip install bs4
!pip install html5lib
!pip install lxml
!pip install plotly

import pandas as pd
import requests
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

import warnings
# Ignore all warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning)

url = "https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-PY0220EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/project/netflix_data_webpage.html"
data  = requests.get(url).text      #.text method for extracting the HTML content as a string in order to make it readable.
print(data)

# parsing refers to the process of analyzing a string of text or a data structure, to understand its structure and meaning.
soup = BeautifulSoup(data, 'html.parser')
netflix_data = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Date", "Open", "High", "Low", "Close", "Volume"])

# use BeautifulSoup method for extracting data
# The find() method  will return particular tag content.
# The find_all() method returns a list of all matching tags in the HTML.
# First we isolate the body of the table which contains all the information
# Then we loop through each row and find all the column values for each row
for row in soup.find("tbody").find_all('tr'):
    col = row.find_all("td")
    date = col[0].text
    Open = col[1].text
    high = col[2].text
    low = col[3].text
    close = col[4].text
    adj_close = col[5].text
    volume = col[6].text
    
    # Finally we append the data of each row to the table
    netflix_data = pd.concat([netflix_data,pd.DataFrame({"Date":[date], "Open":[Open], "High":[high], "Low":[low], "Close":[close], "Adj Close":[adj_close], "Volume":[volume]})], ignore_index=True)    

print(netflix_data.head())

# pd.read_html(url) is a function provided by the pandas library that is used to extract tables from HTML web pages.
read_html_pandas_data = pd.read_html(url)

# read_html_pandas_data = pd.read_html(str(soup))             # convert the BeautifulSoup object to a string

netflix_dataframe = read_html_pandas_data[0]
netflix_dataframe.head()

# Summary of the Process:
# 1. Install Libraries: Install the necessary Python libraries for data manipulation, web scraping, and parsing HTML.
# 2. Import Libraries: Import the libraries required for fetching and processing the HTML content.
# 3. Suppress Warnings: Ignore future warnings to keep the output clean.
# 4. Fetch HTML Content: Use the requests library to download the HTML content from a specified URL and print it to verify.
# 5. Parse HTML: Use BeautifulSoup to parse the HTML content and create a structured representation of the data.
# 6. Initialize DataFrame: Create an empty DataFrame with columns for the data you will extract.
# 7. Extract and Store Data: Iterate over the rows in the HTML table, extract the relevant data from each cell,
#    and append it to the DataFrame.
# 8. Display Data: Print the first few rows of the DataFrame to verify the extracted data.
# 9. Alternative Method: Use pd.read_html() to directly extract tables from the HTML and create a DataFrame.
#    Display the first few rows of this DataFrame.

url = "https://cf-courses-data.s3.us.cloud-object-storage.appdomain.cloud/IBMDeveloperSkillsNetwork-PY0220EN-SkillsNetwork/labs/project/netflix_data_webpage.html"

# Extract table data using pandas
read_html_pandas_data = pd.read_html(url)

# Assuming the first table is the one we want
netflix_dataframe = read_html_pandas_data[0]

# Display the first few rows of the dataframe
print(netflix_dataframe.head())
